00:01:02.040 --> 00:01:06.860
I have to admit that
the title of this panel

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:12.615
is a little bit more pessimistic
than my own view of the future

00:01:12.615 --> 00:01:15.076
of investigative journalism.

00:01:15.076 --> 00:01:17.450
And I'm going to just put out
a couple of quick thoughts.

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:20.010
And obviously, I know
my panelists here

00:01:20.010 --> 00:01:22.780
will be quick to
disagree, if they do.

00:01:22.780 --> 00:01:24.860
But that also makes
good conversation.

00:01:27.630 --> 00:01:32.000
The reason for my own optimism
is that with the internet,

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:36.580
we have, obviously, this
tremendous ability for everyone

00:01:36.580 --> 00:01:39.570
with good thoughts to
get them out there.

00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:41.080
We're not going
through gatekeepers.

00:01:41.080 --> 00:01:44.530
In fact, the very fact that
these organizations exist

00:01:44.530 --> 00:01:48.780
is because we have this
extraordinary thing called

00:01:48.780 --> 00:01:50.930
the internet.

00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:55.260
Secondly, I think we have
incredible new capabilities

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:59.970
available to us today to do
investigative work-- data

00:01:59.970 --> 00:02:06.370
journalism being a
very key part of that.

00:02:06.370 --> 00:02:08.139
And actually,
that's particularly

00:02:08.139 --> 00:02:13.420
important in a world where big
data is increasingly important,

00:02:13.420 --> 00:02:15.110
both for good and for bad.

00:02:15.110 --> 00:02:17.020
We see it abused and disabused.

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:19.270
And certainly the
role of the press

00:02:19.270 --> 00:02:25.020
in shining a light on how big
data is used with big data

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:29.470
analysis of its own, I
think, is really crucial.

00:02:29.470 --> 00:02:32.720
And in that regard, not
only data journalism,

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:34.450
but I think we
have-- as you guys

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:40.180
have shown-- the opportunity
now to actually put out

00:02:40.180 --> 00:02:44.290
important information
in different ways.

00:02:44.290 --> 00:02:49.640
In past realms, investigative
reporting was an article.

00:02:49.640 --> 00:02:54.680
Or five minutes on "60
Minutes" for a story.

00:02:54.680 --> 00:02:57.000
But we can now do things
in different ways.

00:02:57.000 --> 00:02:59.480
You can-- as
ProPublica has done--

00:02:59.480 --> 00:03:00.820
create, in a sense, knowledge.

00:03:00.820 --> 00:03:06.380
Utilities that are evergreen
and can provide ongoing value

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:10.360
to audiences beyond the
instance of the article.

00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:14.200
I think these are hugely
important attributes

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:17.440
to the ecosystem as it evolves.

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:20.390
And while not every
one might agree,

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:22.060
I would actually
put forth that I

00:03:22.060 --> 00:03:24.990
think the state of
investigative journalism today

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:28.670
is even today better than
what it was 20 years ago.

00:03:28.670 --> 00:03:33.580
I think there's been no
small degree of romantization

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:36.940
of the past performance
of traditional media,

00:03:36.940 --> 00:03:40.120
when it comes to
investigative journalism.

00:03:40.120 --> 00:03:42.450
And now we have, I
think, many more voices

00:03:42.450 --> 00:03:45.060
participating in doing
interesting things.

00:03:45.060 --> 00:03:47.060
But even if I'm wrong in
my current assessment,

00:03:47.060 --> 00:03:49.540
I think the opportunity,
the potential,

00:03:49.540 --> 00:03:53.470
to do more and do more
interesting things is really

00:03:53.470 --> 00:03:55.750
quite significant.

00:03:55.750 --> 00:03:59.920
But I'm sure you guys will jump
in and tell me where I'm wrong.

00:03:59.920 --> 00:04:04.720
And I am, on a regular basis, as
many people in this room know.

00:04:04.720 --> 00:04:06.950
We won't pretend.

00:04:06.950 --> 00:04:09.630
So first, let me do just
a very quick introduction

00:04:09.630 --> 00:04:10.400
of our panelists.

00:04:10.400 --> 00:04:13.300
Because then I'd like to turn
to them individually and let

00:04:13.300 --> 00:04:16.660
them say a little bit
more about themselves,

00:04:16.660 --> 00:04:19.640
their organizations,
and frankly, what

00:04:19.640 --> 00:04:23.150
drives their passion in
doing what they're doing.

00:04:23.150 --> 00:04:26.430
And particularly today,
because you are, really,

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:30.700
at the creative edge of
investigative journalism today.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:34.570
So we have Robin Fields,
managing editor of ProPublica.

00:04:34.570 --> 00:04:37.962
ProPublica has been
around now, what?

00:04:37.962 --> 00:04:39.003
ROBIN FIELDS: Since 2008.

00:04:39.003 --> 00:04:40.780
RICHARD GINGRAS: Since 2008.

00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:42.990
has done a tremendous
amount of exquisite work.

00:04:42.990 --> 00:04:46.640
Won, what, two Pulitzers now?

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:50.277
Just giving an indication of
the impact that they've had.

00:04:50.277 --> 00:04:51.360
So great to hear from you.

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:53.970
And I know I've been
in my own conversations

00:04:53.970 --> 00:04:56.970
with Paul Steiger
and Dick Tofel,

00:04:56.970 --> 00:04:58.710
it's just been very
impressive to see

00:04:58.710 --> 00:05:00.870
how the organization
has evolved.

00:05:00.870 --> 00:05:02.760
In fact, Dick mentioned
to me recently

00:05:02.760 --> 00:05:06.970
