making money off of your data,

00:05:06.970 --> 00:05:10.350
which I'd love to hear more
about when we get to that.

00:05:10.350 --> 00:05:14.640
Alisa Barba is executive
editor of Inside Energy.

00:05:14.640 --> 00:05:18.930
Again, the kind of
organization and editorial

00:05:18.930 --> 00:05:23.560
focus that we wouldn't likely
have seen 20, 30 years ago--

00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:30.350
that focus on a specific
area where people feel

00:05:30.350 --> 00:05:32.460
there's an important
amount of journalistic work

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:34.142
that needs to be done.

00:05:34.142 --> 00:05:36.100
So we'll love to hear
more about those efforts.

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:39.100
And then Andy Donohue
from the Center

00:05:39.100 --> 00:05:43.310
for Investigative Reporting,
based over in Berkeley,

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:49.220
which has also done just ongoing
superb investigative work.

00:05:49.220 --> 00:05:52.110
Superb work in
beginning to evolve

00:05:52.110 --> 00:05:57.800
the models of engagement,
of presentation, of how

00:05:57.800 --> 00:06:02.740
one builds a credible brand
in the world of the internet

00:06:02.740 --> 00:06:05.320
and works to get the
results of your efforts

00:06:05.320 --> 00:06:07.660
out to ever-larger audiences.

00:06:07.660 --> 00:06:11.830
So I'm really honored to
have you all here today.

00:06:11.830 --> 00:06:14.240
I think it's so important
for all of us here at Google

00:06:14.240 --> 00:06:20.000
to really see the faces
and the people who

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.420
do this extraordinarily
important work.

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:28.660
Who take the risks and toil
hard for what is not likely

00:06:28.660 --> 00:06:32.860
the most remunerative profession
you could have selected.

00:06:32.860 --> 00:06:36.440
So we'll start with Andy.

00:06:36.440 --> 00:06:38.830
A little bit more about
yourself and what drives you.

00:06:38.830 --> 00:06:39.830
ANDY ANDY DONOHUE: Sure.

00:06:39.830 --> 00:06:44.810
So I had sort of an
interesting moment college,

00:06:44.810 --> 00:06:47.040
actually, as a
college journalist,

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:49.030
where I was working on
one of my first stories

00:06:49.030 --> 00:06:51.260
and trying to think of some
different ways of doing

00:06:51.260 --> 00:06:51.760
a story.

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:54.640
And I had my editor
tell me, "There

00:06:54.640 --> 00:06:57.740
is no creativity in journalism."

00:06:57.740 --> 00:07:00.260
That was a pretty
dispiriting remark

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:01.990
to hear as somebody
who was just getting

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:05.870
started who was really
interested in journalism,

00:07:05.870 --> 00:07:08.207
but also trying to
think about doing things

00:07:08.207 --> 00:07:09.290
in a little different way.

00:07:09.290 --> 00:07:13.630
And what has been, I think,
most exciting to me in my career

00:07:13.630 --> 00:07:15.710
and what's changed
in the last, maybe,

00:07:15.710 --> 00:07:18.900
10 years is not that
there wasn't creativity

00:07:18.900 --> 00:07:22.400
in journalism, but it's really
being unleashed right now.

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:24.340
You just have so many
different models.

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:26.550
So many different
ways of storytelling.

00:07:26.550 --> 00:07:29.370
And so many different types
of organizations and types

00:07:29.370 --> 00:07:30.060
of reporting.

00:07:30.060 --> 00:07:31.010
Different technology.

00:07:31.010 --> 00:07:33.810
That not only is creativity
part of journalism,

00:07:33.810 --> 00:07:36.810
but it's really, really,
highly valued right now.

00:07:36.810 --> 00:07:41.050
And it's part of the lifeboat,
everybody understanding

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:46.800
that this is how we
create the new journalism.

00:07:46.800 --> 00:07:51.780
My background is,
before being at CIR,

00:07:51.780 --> 00:07:54.330
I was a Knight
Fellow at Stanford.

00:07:54.330 --> 00:07:56.390
And then also,
before that, I was

00:07:56.390 --> 00:07:59.650
at Voice of San Diego,
which was a start-up-- one

00:07:59.650 --> 00:08:03.630
of the first nonprofit
start-ups to pop up.

00:08:03.630 --> 00:08:06.920
We basically were
created because people

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:10.590
were very unhappy with the
local media in San Diego

00:08:10.590 --> 00:08:13.580
and had wanted to create a
new publication for a really

00:08:13.580 --> 00:08:14.750
long time.

00:08:14.750 --> 00:08:17.100
And every time
they looked at it,

00:08:17.100 --> 00:08:22.390
they would get into the cost
of trying to print a newspaper,

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:24.990
buy all the paper, get
the trucks, the gas.

00:08:24.990 --> 00:08:27.920
All that infrastructure
took up 2/3 of your costs.

00:08:27.920 --> 00:08:29.920
And so it never made
sense, and they could never

00:08:29.920 --> 00:08:31.710
scale it in an interesting way.

00:08:31.710 --> 00:08:34.650
And then in about
2004, we sort of

00:08:34.650 --> 00:08:40.750
realized that the internet was
ready to hold a legitimate news

00:08:40.750 --> 00:08:42.220
organization.

00:08:42.220 --> 00:08:44.090
And that for-profit
wasn't the way

00:08:44.090 --> 00:08:48.230
to go, because the
advertising revenue was

00:08:48.230 --> 00:08:50.030
starting to decline,
or going to decline.

00:08:50.030 --> 00:08:54.180
So we went non-profit,
and that's, I guess,

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:57.760
the model that supports
all three of us here.

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:00.940
ALISA ALISA BARBA:
Yeah, for good or bad.

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:05.669
So I go back a lot
farther than a lot

00:09:05.669 --> 00:09:07.460
of people working in
journalism these days.

00:09:07.460 --> 00:09:10.010
And I was thinking about
this as I was coming up here,

00:09:10.010 --> 00:09:11.660
because part of what we're
going to be talking about

00:09:11.660 --> 00:09:13.610
is the tools that we
use to do what we do.

00:09:13.610 --> 00:09:16.670
And I was thinking
about my earliest tool.

00:09:16.670 --> 00:09:20.200
This was 30 years ago,
and I was a news clipper

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:23.121
in the Newsweek
office in Beijing.

00:09:23.121 --> 00:09:24.620
So that was my first
journalism job.

00:09:24.620 --> 00:09:25.740
And there was this
little, teeny tool--

00:09:25.740 --> 00:09:27.323
I don't know if
anybody remembers it--

00:09:27.323 --> 00:09:29.670
where you could actually
cut through the newspapers.

00:09:29.670 --> 00:09:30.170
Right?

00:09:30.170 --> 00:09:31.067
You remember those?

00:09:31.067 --> 00:09:32.900
I went looking for it
this morning to bring.

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:33.775
I wanted to show you.

00:09:33.775 --> 00:09:35.344
You'd clip the
newspaper articles

00:09:35.344 --> 00:09:37.010
and you'd stick it
in a folder and you'd

00:09:37.010 --> 00:09:38.500
stick it in a big
filing cabinet.

00:09:38.500 --> 00:09:40.990
And this was your source
of information for stories

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:41.936
that you were doing.

00:09:41.936 --> 00:09:46.680
You had communism, Maoism,
agriculture, whatever.

00:09:46.680 --> 00:09:48.770
And in those days-- I
was trying to remember.

00:09:48.770 --> 00:09:50.974
I think, was it teletype
machine to send the stories

00:09:50.974 --> 00:09:51.515
from Beijing?

00:09:51.515 --> 00:09:52.860
I don't even remember.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:55.090
It eventually evolved
to fax machines.

00:09:55.090 --> 00:09:57.270
And then, obviously, to today.

00:09:57.270 --> 00:10:01.910
So Inside Energy, the
group that I work with,

00:10:01.910 --> 00:10:05.240
is very, very small, certainly
compared to these guys.

00:10:05.240 --> 00:10:07.610
I have five reporters on staff.

00:10:07.610 --> 00:10:08.760
One is a data journalist.

00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:11.860
We're in the center of the
country-- Denver, Wyoming,

00:10:11.860 --> 00:10:13.710
and North Dakota.

00:10:13.710 --> 00:10:15.570
We're covering the energy boom.

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:18.050
What's going on there.

00:10:18.050 --> 00:10:19.850
And we're trying
to figure it out.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:21.058
We're trying to make it work.

00:10:21.058 --> 00:10:21.920
We're public media.

00:10:21.920 --> 00:10:23.950
We do television
and we do radio.

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:27.000
And we also do digital,
obviously, as everybody does.

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.600
We have one data journalist.

00:10:29.600 --> 00:10:31.990
And we're trying to go
deep into these stories

00:10:31.990 --> 00:10:36.185
and uncover the good, the bad,
and the ugly about the oil

00:10:36.185 --> 00:10:37.960
and gas boom and
what's going on there.

00:10:37.960 --> 00:10:39.720
We're doing it with
a very small staff.

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:43.330
And I have some really great
questions for you guys,

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:44.130
when that comes.

00:10:44.130 --> 00:10:45.088
RICHARD GINGRAS: Great.

00:10:45.088 --> 00:10:46.704
And Robin.

00:10:46.704 --> 00:10:50.250
ROBIN FIELDS: I started
at ProPublica in 2008,

00:10:50.250 --> 00:10:55.440
when it was mostly an empty room
and sort of an idea for what

00:10:55.440 --> 00:10:57.410
we'd like to accomplish.

00:10:57.410 --> 00:11:02.260
And our mission has
always been to do stories

00:11:02.260 --> 00:11:05.670
that have an impact
and that spark change.

00:11:05.670 --> 00:11:08.510
And it's been amazing to
see, over the six years

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:12.120
that I've been there,
that we've been

00:11:12.120 --> 00:11:14.390
able to accomplish that so much.

00:11:14.390 --> 00:11:18.220
It's just been an
amazing ride so far.

00:11:18.220 --> 00:11:19.340
We are nonprofit.

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:21.610
Today we are not an
empty room at all.

00:11:21.610 --> 00:11:24.230
We're almost squeezing
out of our original space.

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:27.710
We're 45 journalists,
ten of whom

00:11:27.710 --> 00:11:31.360
are basically data
journalists and developers.

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:36.540
And as Richard was saying,
data and data applications

00:11:36.540 --> 00:11:41.100
are central to our work and
central to our mission, in that

00:11:41.100 --> 00:11:44.190
not only do they allow us
to do the stories that we do

00:11:44.190 --> 00:11:50.120
and sort of quantify things
and use tools that journalists

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:53.440
didn't used to use, but
they allow other reporters

00:11:53.440 --> 00:11:56.570
to take our stories
and localize them.

00:11:56.570 --> 00:11:58.850
Our Dollars for
Docs application,

00:11:58.850 --> 00:12:00.640
for example-- which
is just one of them--

00:12:00.640 --> 00:12:05.050
has been used by something like
180 other news organizations

00:12:05.050 --> 00:12:07.590
to write stories of their own.

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:10.230
And it shows you how
an organization that's

00:12:10.230 --> 00:12:12.690
45 people, most of
them in New York,

00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:17.470
can have a ripple effect
that goes on and on.

00:12:17.470 --> 00:12:22.120
And I think that so
much of our challenge

00:12:22.120 --> 00:12:26.210
is always to-- as you
were saying-- be creative.

00:12:26.210 --> 00:12:31.540
Cut through the outrage fatigue,
the numbness, the noise,

00:12:31.540 --> 00:12:37.920
to try to do stories that stay
with people and do make change.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:42.740
So that's pretty much our story.

00:12:42.740 --> 00:12:45.090
RICHARD GINGRAS: As
I noted, each of you

00:12:45.090 --> 00:12:48.500
are in relatively
new organizations.

00:12:48.500 --> 00:12:53.195
CIR has been around the
longest in a pre-digital form,

00:12:53.195 --> 00:12:55.701
actually.

00:12:55.701 --> 00:12:57.450
But given that, and
given your experience,

00:12:57.450 --> 00:13:00.020
and given that all three
of you really come out

00:13:00.020 --> 00:13:01.790
of traditional
media organizations

00:13:01.790 --> 00:13:05.820
in your backgrounds-- what's
the advice you would give the LA

00:13:05.820 --> 00:13:10.860
Times, ABC News, as they
struggle with change?

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:14.980
Do you do you have
any advice for them?

00:13:14.980 --> 00:13:17.820
ANDY DONOHUE: I think
maybe one thing would

00:13:17.820 --> 00:13:20.630
be not to try to be
everything to everybody.

00:13:20.630 --> 00:13:23.020
I mean, there's one
thing, one of the threads

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:25.270
you can run through all
of us, which is really

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:28.200
trying to be specialized and
focused in certain things.

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:29.950
And that's what you're
seeing in all kinds

00:13:29.950 --> 00:13:32.460
of different start-ups
whether they be the Marshall

00:13:32.460 --> 00:13:36.040
project, which is a new
nonprofit start-up that's just

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:39.740
about criminal justice
issues, or if it's Vox, just

00:13:39.740 --> 00:13:41.900
about explaining things.

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:43.910
And even you see the
New York Times sort

00:13:43.910 --> 00:13:46.330
of moving this way
now, that they're

00:13:46.330 --> 00:13:47.900
starting to build
more micro-sites.

00:13:47.900 --> 00:13:50.060
They have a whole cooking
site, which has totally

00:13:50.060 --> 00:13:52.660
revolutionized the
eating in my family.

00:13:52.660 --> 00:13:56.750
They've got The Upshot,
which is sort of election.

00:13:56.750 --> 00:13:59.710
The internet organizes
itself around communities.

00:13:59.710 --> 00:14:03.204
It doesn't really organize
itself around general interest.

00:14:03.204 --> 00:14:04.620
And so what you're
starting to see

00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:09.100
is just a lot more organizing
around communities.

00:14:09.100 --> 00:14:11.290
And what it looks like is,
you organize communities

00:14:11.290 --> 00:14:13.370
and then maybe if you
organize a bunch of them,

00:14:13.370 --> 00:14:17.012
then it ends up becoming general
interest in some of them.

00:14:17.012 --> 00:14:17.970
RICHARD GINGRAS: Robin?

00:14:17.970 --> 00:14:20.100
Alisa?

00:14:20.100 --> 00:14:25.455
ROBIN FIELDS: Well, I think that
what we were seeing happening

00:14:25.455 --> 00:14:26.830
in a lot of these
organizations--

00:14:26.830 --> 00:14:33.650
the idea that you could cut your
way to the future-- I think,

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:36.420
people have sort of realised
the futility of that.

00:14:36.420 --> 00:14:38.970
And I think the path
forward probably does

00:14:38.970 --> 00:14:42.470
lie exactly where
Andy was saying.

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:46.070
I think that it's tough to--
it's kind of like they're

00:14:46.070 --> 00:14:48.600
trying to take this giant
Lincoln Continental.

00:14:48.600 --> 00:14:51.300
They're driving down the
highway at 60 miles an hour

00:14:51.300 --> 00:14:52.720
and trying to turn
it into a Prius

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:54.270
while they're still driving it.

00:14:54.270 --> 00:14:58.205
And I in some ways have a
lot of compassion for that,

00:14:58.205 --> 00:14:59.830
because they still
have to deal with so

00:14:59.830 --> 00:15:03.430
many of the expectations
of the past.

00:15:03.430 --> 00:15:06.000
And also, so much
of their revenue

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.500
is still coming from paper.

00:15:09.500 --> 00:15:13.950
So I guess if I had a business
model that would work for them,

00:15:13.950 --> 00:15:16.450
I'd probably be in a different
line of work than I am today.

00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:19.010
But I don't think that
they have the option

00:15:19.010 --> 00:15:22.940
of going non-profit and
funding themselves our way.

00:15:22.940 --> 00:15:24.860
So they're going
to have a soldier

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:26.780
forward in a different way.

00:15:26.780 --> 00:15:28.780
ALISA BARBA: And those
organizations-- you know,

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:30.780
the LA Times, the New
York Times, all those guys

00:15:30.780 --> 00:15:34.030
--they're still built
on fabulous reporters,

00:15:34.030 --> 00:15:35.290
great storytelling.

00:15:35.290 --> 00:15:37.840
And I think that what we
have learned, whether you're

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:40.760
in the profit or the
non-profit sector,

00:15:40.760 --> 00:15:43.110
is that great reporting
will find a way

00:15:43.110 --> 00:15:45.310
to pay for itself,
one way or the other.

00:15:45.310 --> 00:15:48.910
Whether it's smaller,
leaner, deeper.

00:15:48.910 --> 00:15:50.627
Those are the key elements.

00:15:50.627 --> 00:15:52.210
RICHARD GINGRAS:
Well so far, anyways,

00:15:52.210 --> 00:15:55.490
it seems that at
least in your efforts,

00:15:55.490 --> 00:15:59.340
that great reporting
is finding a way.

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:02.600
But let me go to the other
extreme and ask you this.

00:16:02.600 --> 00:16:06.120
As I said, I have a
