00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:09.170
from an architectural
perspective.

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:10.860
But what scares you?

00:16:10.860 --> 00:16:14.240
What makes you
nervous as you try

00:16:14.240 --> 00:16:16.134
to move your efforts forward?

00:16:16.134 --> 00:16:17.550
ALISA BARBA: I'll
just say that we

00:16:17.550 --> 00:16:20.980
are funded right now through
a grant from the Corporation

00:16:20.980 --> 00:16:23.000
for Public Broadcasting,
which has sought

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.830
to foster local journalism
centers across the country.

00:16:26.830 --> 00:16:30.740
So what I'm scared of is
when the CPB money goes away.

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:33.090
So basically, when our
grant funding ends,

00:16:33.090 --> 00:16:35.330
we have to find a model
for sustainability that

00:16:35.330 --> 00:16:37.577
is going to be something
along the lines of what

00:16:37.577 --> 00:16:38.160
these guys do.

00:16:38.160 --> 00:16:40.090
But again, we're
only six, seven.

00:16:40.090 --> 00:16:43.030
And we're based
in states without

00:16:43.030 --> 00:16:45.620
a huge philanthropic community.

00:16:45.620 --> 00:16:47.190
We're not New York
or San Francisco.

00:16:47.190 --> 00:16:49.310
We're in North
Dakota and Wyoming,

00:16:49.310 --> 00:16:52.780
and frankly a lot of
people in those states

00:16:52.780 --> 00:16:55.770
don't listen to public radio
and don't watch public TV.

00:16:55.770 --> 00:16:58.630
I think the what they call the
cume-- the amount of people who

00:16:58.630 --> 00:17:02.340
listen to us, it's maybe 5%
to 10% on a really good--

00:17:02.340 --> 00:17:04.690
really good-- week.

00:17:04.690 --> 00:17:08.109
So finding sustainability
within these local communities

00:17:08.109 --> 00:17:11.339
is really the nut that
we're trying to crack.

00:17:11.339 --> 00:17:16.730
And if you look at, I think,
large national organizations--

00:17:16.730 --> 00:17:19.050
which these guys
both qualify as-- you

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:20.869
have a better,
easier, time of it

00:17:20.869 --> 00:17:23.580
frankly, than local
non-profit journalists.

00:17:26.160 --> 00:17:28.550
RICHARD GINGRAS: So
we're going to actually

00:17:28.550 --> 00:17:29.790
go to questions, shortly.

00:17:29.790 --> 00:17:33.640
In fact, we have
the Dory somewhere.

00:17:33.640 --> 00:17:35.940
The Dory is our internal
tool so that anyone

00:17:35.940 --> 00:17:37.730
can surface questions
for this gathering.

00:17:37.730 --> 00:17:39.976
They don't have to
be here in the room.

00:17:39.976 --> 00:17:41.350
And I'm sure there
are good ones,

00:17:41.350 --> 00:17:45.250
and we'll begin
with those shortly.

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:46.630
In fact, gladly begin now.

00:17:46.630 --> 00:17:50.280
If there's a question in the
room, we can go right to that.

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:52.490
Open this up broadly.

00:17:52.490 --> 00:17:53.406
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:17:59.040 --> 00:18:06.268
So given the funding challenges,
are news organizations

00:18:06.268 --> 00:18:10.754
starting to do less emphasis on
the exclusive and more emphasis

00:18:10.754 --> 00:18:11.680
on finding the story?

00:18:11.680 --> 00:18:13.763
Whether that would mean
aligning with competitors.

00:18:13.763 --> 00:18:19.000
Another way the movie
industry [INAUDIBLE]

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.880
came together to [INAUDIBLE].

00:18:25.940 --> 00:18:27.500
ROBIN FIELDS: Well,
speaking for us,

00:18:27.500 --> 00:18:33.510
we've always been sort of a
serial collaborator or partner.

00:18:33.510 --> 00:18:36.320
We're always looking to partner
with other news organizations

00:18:36.320 --> 00:18:37.290
on our stories.

00:18:37.290 --> 00:18:39.080
And I think that
it's interesting

00:18:39.080 --> 00:18:41.590
because we've seen
investigative reporting-- which

00:18:41.590 --> 00:18:45.070
was once just perceived
as super-competitive, only

00:18:45.070 --> 00:18:48.530
competitive, only
"mine, mine, mine" kind

00:18:48.530 --> 00:18:51.930
of an attitude-- change
completely into something where

00:18:51.930 --> 00:18:55.110
we want people to not only
partner with us on our stories,

00:18:55.110 --> 00:18:57.120
we want them to
follow stories, do

00:18:57.120 --> 00:18:59.270
stories modeled on our stories.

00:18:59.270 --> 00:19:02.490
We routinely release
our stories and then

00:19:02.490 --> 00:19:04.890
put out a reporter's
recipe for our stories

00:19:04.890 --> 00:19:09.290
to spark other
people's journalism.

00:19:09.290 --> 00:19:12.080
Because ultimately,
for us the mission

00:19:12.080 --> 00:19:14.320
isn't just to be able to
stamp a giant "ProPublica"

00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:16.610
on everything--
although that's fine,

00:19:16.610 --> 00:19:20.180
so if you want to do
that, go right ahead--

00:19:20.180 --> 00:19:22.720
but to have an
impact in this world.

00:19:22.720 --> 00:19:25.690
And have a story that
makes a difference.

00:19:25.690 --> 00:19:29.370
So we have partnered
probably with,

00:19:29.370 --> 00:19:31.850
at this point, a couple
hundred news organizations.

00:19:31.850 --> 00:19:36.060
And we're always looking
to find new partners.

00:19:36.060 --> 00:19:38.830
So yes, in answer to that.

00:19:38.830 --> 00:19:41.850
ANDY DONOHUE: I think that's
a really important result

00:19:41.850 --> 00:19:45.440
of this business model, is that
when you do talk to funders

00:19:45.440 --> 00:19:48.330
they want to know what the
impact of your story is.

00:19:48.330 --> 00:19:50.530
I mean, that's what
they're putting money into

00:19:50.530 --> 00:19:51.850
and that's what they've funded.

00:19:51.850 --> 00:19:54.850
They're used funding other
things like education reform

00:19:54.850 --> 00:19:56.810
or environmentalism,
where they do

00:19:56.810 --> 00:19:58.832
want to see the impact of that.

00:19:58.832 --> 00:20:00.290
Sometimes it's a
fine line to walk.

00:20:00.290 --> 00:20:03.010
We can't be political
advocates for certain things.

00:20:03.010 --> 00:20:05.940
But that's generally not
that hard to figure out.

00:20:05.940 --> 00:20:10.160
But what they don't care
is who gets the credit.

00:20:10.160 --> 00:20:12.144
Unless it's them.

00:20:12.144 --> 00:20:15.290
Just kidding.

00:20:15.290 --> 00:20:16.540
We've partnered.

00:20:16.540 --> 00:20:18.071
Even though you
could say that we

00:20:18.071 --> 00:20:19.820
compete for maybe some
of the same grants,

00:20:19.820 --> 00:20:20.778
or something like that.

00:20:20.778 --> 00:20:22.940
We've partnered on
stories together.

00:20:22.940 --> 00:20:25.550
But a really
important part of that

00:20:25.550 --> 00:20:30.340
is localizing data so
that when we do a story,

00:20:30.340 --> 00:20:32.820
and we'll get statewide
or nationwide data,

00:20:32.820 --> 00:20:35.370
we are in an active
pursuit of trying

00:20:35.370 --> 00:20:38.817
to find local publications
to get that out and do that.

00:20:38.817 --> 00:20:40.900
And that's just a whole
different world in the way

00:20:40.900 --> 00:20:42.850
that we collaborate
than we used to.

00:20:42.850 --> 00:20:43.641
ALISA BARBA: Right.

00:20:43.641 --> 00:20:45.340
And so we, as a
small organization,

00:20:45.340 --> 00:20:48.260
we can take the data
from one of these guys

00:20:48.260 --> 00:20:50.730
if they're doing a big
data dive on some story.

00:20:50.730 --> 00:20:53.890
And not only can we
localize it, but we can

00:20:53.890 --> 00:20:56.070
also-- we're in
different mediums.

00:20:56.070 --> 00:20:57.760
So I do radio and television.

00:20:57.760 --> 00:21:00.256
So a lot of these guys
focus is on print.

00:21:00.256 --> 00:21:02.380
[INAUDIBLE] does a lot of
radio and television too.

00:21:02.380 --> 00:21:04.670
But I can put you on NPR.

00:21:04.670 --> 00:21:07.250
I can get that megaphone
onto your story,

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:09.300
which is always good.

00:21:09.300 --> 00:21:11.630
RICHARD GINGRAS: In fact,
all three of you, all three

00:21:11.630 --> 00:21:15.010
of your organizations
do, in a sense,

00:21:15.010 --> 00:21:19.930
syndicate your content in a
quest for larger audiences.

00:21:19.930 --> 00:21:21.560
Last time I talked
to Robert Rosenthal,

00:21:21.560 --> 00:21:23.059
he was talking about
how much effort

00:21:23.059 --> 00:21:24.900
you put into measuring
impact, which I think

00:21:24.900 --> 00:21:27.630
is a great thing to do.

00:21:27.630 --> 00:21:29.960
But you, I know, had
a question before,

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:32.790
which I think would be
good to raise for the group

00:21:32.790 --> 00:21:34.780
and see if we can find
an answer for you.

00:21:34.780 --> 00:21:37.470
ALISA BARBA: OK, so, again, this
is a small news organization's

00:21:37.470 --> 00:21:37.970
problem.

00:21:37.970 --> 00:21:42.270
This is not probably
their problem.

00:21:42.270 --> 00:21:44.620
Inside Energy is our group.

00:21:44.620 --> 00:21:46.830
We have our website,
insideenergy.org,

00:21:46.830 --> 00:21:49.030
and we all put a lot of
attention into our website.

00:21:49.030 --> 00:21:49.630
We make it pretty.

00:21:49.630 --> 00:21:50.504
We make it beautiful.

00:21:50.504 --> 00:21:51.900
We do a lot of data.

00:21:51.900 --> 00:21:55.285
Then we also have seven
partners across our region

00:21:55.285 --> 00:21:58.714
who take our digital content
and put it on their sites

00:21:58.714 --> 00:22:00.880
as well, because they don't
have anybody doing this.

00:22:00.880 --> 00:22:04.080
So part of our mission
is to raise capacity.

00:22:04.080 --> 00:22:06.970
Is to take smaller newsrooms
and give them news stories

00:22:06.970 --> 00:22:09.360
that they can put on there
and make them sound better.

00:22:09.360 --> 00:22:11.470
But digitally, that screws us.

00:22:11.470 --> 00:22:13.930
We lose our juice
when our one story

00:22:13.930 --> 00:22:16.420
is on seven different
digital platforms.

00:22:16.420 --> 00:22:19.850
So, Google, do you guys
have a solution for me?

00:22:19.850 --> 00:22:20.770
What can I do?

00:22:20.770 --> 00:22:22.860
I know we can customize
all the local content

00:22:22.860 --> 00:22:23.776
and make it different.

00:22:23.776 --> 00:22:26.390
But basically that's
been a huge problem.

00:22:26.390 --> 00:22:30.840
RICHARD GINGRAS: In a sense,
how to maintain your Google

00:22:30.840 --> 00:22:33.510
juice, as it were?

00:22:33.510 --> 00:22:36.290
ALISA BARBA: Here's the issue,
is that our own website-- we're

00:22:36.290 --> 00:22:38.030
supposed to be
serving our partners.

00:22:38.030 --> 00:22:39.930
We're supposed to make
them all look better.

00:22:39.930 --> 00:22:42.560
Our website, the way we
sold it to them, we said,

00:22:42.560 --> 00:22:43.660
we're just archival. .

00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:45.340
We just need a little
place to put it

00:22:45.340 --> 00:22:48.100
but we're doing all kinds
of digital-only content

00:22:48.100 --> 00:22:52.230
that our partners are reluctant
to publish because of the fact

00:22:52.230 --> 00:22:55.215
that it basically doesn't
seem to raise all boats.

00:22:55.215 --> 00:22:58.054
Does that make sense?

00:22:58.054 --> 00:22:59.220
RICHARD GINGRAS: I think so.

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:01.840
I'll touch on one part of it,
and if others have perspective

00:23:01.840 --> 00:23:05.850
in the room, I'd
like you to jump in.

00:23:05.850 --> 00:23:08.860
Because one thing-- and
what I was picking up

00:23:08.860 --> 00:23:11.690
in earlier conversations--
is that issue of,

00:23:11.690 --> 00:23:15.140
if we're syndicating
our content,

00:23:15.140 --> 00:23:18.120
how do we do it in
such a fashion that we

00:23:18.120 --> 00:23:21.940
as the organization and
wrote the canonical article,

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:25.580
in a sense, retain
primary value.

00:23:25.580 --> 00:23:27.400
Which, by the way,
is not a question

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:30.540
that just comes from
small organizations.

00:23:30.540 --> 00:23:34.250
The New York Times,
obviously, syndicates content.

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:36.910
And we've had similar
discussions with them.

00:23:36.910 --> 00:23:41.520
So in that specific point, there
are some things you can do.

00:23:41.520 --> 00:23:44.320
The simplest right now is
simply to have your syndication

00:23:44.320 --> 00:23:48.310
partners, when they're putting
your content on their sites,

00:23:48.310 --> 00:23:50.040
is to make sure
there's a "noindex"

00:23:50.040 --> 00:23:55.990
tag in the articles, which
means that we won't crawl that.

00:23:55.990 --> 00:23:57.720
We won't include
that in our index.

00:23:57.720 --> 00:23:59.670
We'll actually then find yours.

00:23:59.670 --> 00:24:02.470
There's another tag
called "rel=canonical"

00:24:02.470 --> 00:24:03.670
which you can also use.

00:24:03.670 --> 00:24:05.130
And ultimately, it
might be better,

00:24:05.130 --> 00:24:10.920
but that is being used across
the industry isn't as clear.

00:24:10.920 --> 00:24:13.220
[INAUDIBLE] Make use of that.

00:24:13.220 --> 00:24:15.760
But others here
might have thoughts

00:24:15.760 --> 00:24:17.740
about your general
question, or correct me

00:24:17.740 --> 00:24:20.430
if they think I'm wrong in my
answer to that specific point.

