with what the truth is.

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:10.250
And we don't like to admit
that, but we're always

00:26:10.250 --> 00:26:11.260
doing that with a story.

00:26:11.260 --> 00:26:12.130
Where you're not quite sure.

00:26:12.130 --> 00:26:13.290
Am I even on this story?

00:26:13.290 --> 00:26:14.281
Is this guy guilty?

00:26:14.281 --> 00:26:14.780
Innocent?

00:26:14.780 --> 00:26:17.990
I mean, just to freely
and openly grapple

00:26:17.990 --> 00:26:20.660
with that, I think,
is really liberating.

00:26:20.660 --> 00:26:24.867
I hope that's a key feature
of investigative reporting

00:26:24.867 --> 00:26:25.450
in the future.

00:26:25.450 --> 00:26:27.410
And then just the quest
narrative, in general,

00:26:27.410 --> 00:26:30.500
is just such a powerful way of
telling a story that we haven't

00:26:30.500 --> 00:26:32.890
really harnessed very much
in investigative reporting,

00:26:32.890 --> 00:26:33.390
as well.

00:26:33.390 --> 00:26:34.540
ALISA BARBA: It just
basically gives us

00:26:34.540 --> 00:26:35.930
a new way to tell a story.

00:26:35.930 --> 00:26:41.330
And I mean, my staff is a
bunch of podcast addicts.

00:26:41.330 --> 00:26:42.875
And they're just
going nuts about it.

00:26:42.875 --> 00:26:45.250
So now every story is going
to become a "Serial" podcast.

00:26:48.934 --> 00:26:50.600
RICHARD GINGRAS:
Question from the Dory?

00:26:50.600 --> 00:26:52.389
Oh, question from Marisha.

00:26:52.389 --> 00:26:56.630
AUDIENCE: That actually
goes into a question

00:26:56.630 --> 00:26:59.375
that I've been wondering.

00:26:59.375 --> 00:27:02.369
I sort of have this [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:18.684 --> 00:27:20.100
ANDY DONOHUE:
That's the fun part.

00:27:20.100 --> 00:27:22.530
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:27:22.530 --> 00:27:25.170
ROBIN FIELDS: Well,
I think we often

00:27:25.170 --> 00:27:28.120
start with a lead or a tip
or something like that.

00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:29.880
But the truth of
the matter is, we

00:27:29.880 --> 00:27:33.010
may have an idea what the
minimum story would be.

00:27:33.010 --> 00:27:37.690
But as my boss is fond of
saying, whenever asked about,

00:27:37.690 --> 00:27:40.106
"What's the best story that
could come out of this?"

00:27:40.106 --> 00:27:42.480
The best story that could come
out of this is one that we

00:27:42.480 --> 00:27:45.290
cannot even imagine today.

00:27:45.290 --> 00:27:46.880
And that's what's
exciting about it.

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:48.950
It's what's volatile about it.

00:27:48.950 --> 00:27:51.970
And in some ways,
investigative stories

00:27:51.970 --> 00:27:56.010
are always the stories where
the people you're writing about,

00:27:56.010 --> 00:27:57.480
or the thing you
are writing about,

00:27:57.480 --> 00:28:00.150
often don't want
you to do the story.

00:28:00.150 --> 00:28:03.890
So they're often stories that
are difficult because you

00:28:03.890 --> 00:28:06.780
get very little cooperation.

00:28:06.780 --> 00:28:09.290
When people get a call from
someone from ProPublica

00:28:09.290 --> 00:28:11.620
they kind of know
the story is not

00:28:11.620 --> 00:28:15.160
going to be puppies, clowns,
the latest press release.

00:28:15.160 --> 00:28:19.070
So we're constantly
having to overcome that.

00:28:19.070 --> 00:28:24.930
And the challenges
and twists and turns

00:28:24.930 --> 00:28:28.020
of an investigative story,
to someone who did them.

00:28:28.020 --> 00:28:30.010
Is endlessly fascinating.

00:28:30.010 --> 00:28:31.630
But the great thing
is you can get

00:28:31.630 --> 00:28:35.690
somewhere way more interesting
and better than you

00:28:35.690 --> 00:28:37.240
ever, ever imagined.

00:28:37.240 --> 00:28:40.960
The truth is usually
stranger than you think.

00:28:40.960 --> 00:28:46.665
RICHARD GINGRAS: Can you give
a few insights into your craft,

00:28:46.665 --> 00:28:47.290
in that regard?

00:28:47.290 --> 00:28:50.810
I mean, I often observe--
I have several friends who

00:28:50.810 --> 00:28:54.950
are reporters, and
I'm always amused

00:28:54.950 --> 00:28:57.670
at how good they are about
getting me to talk about things

00:28:57.670 --> 00:28:59.870
that I wasn't necessarily
comfortable talking about.

00:28:59.870 --> 00:29:03.850
And you're like, "How
did you do that?"

00:29:03.850 --> 00:29:07.844
You're not going to
tell us, are you?

00:29:07.844 --> 00:29:10.010
ROBIN FIELDS: I think that
one of the amazing things

00:29:10.010 --> 00:29:12.030
about a life as a
reporter is you're often

00:29:12.030 --> 00:29:14.795
talking to people on the best
or the worst day of their lives.

00:29:18.520 --> 00:29:20.420
And they do this
amazing thing, which

00:29:20.420 --> 00:29:23.320
is that they trust you
with their stories.

00:29:23.320 --> 00:29:24.700
They trust you with their lives.

00:29:24.700 --> 00:29:29.830
They trust you with these things
that they haven't told anybody

00:29:29.830 --> 00:29:31.040
else, sometimes.

00:29:31.040 --> 00:29:34.630
I mean, we just brought out
this story about Firestone

00:29:34.630 --> 00:29:39.680
in Liberia and their
dealings with Charles Taylor,

00:29:39.680 --> 00:29:41.050
the warlord.

00:29:41.050 --> 00:29:44.470
And one of the crucial
interviews for this story--

00:29:44.470 --> 00:29:47.680
a story that was reported
over the course of a year--

00:29:47.680 --> 00:29:51.850
we didn't get that interview
until maybe a week, or a week

00:29:51.850 --> 00:29:53.540
and a half before publication.

00:29:53.540 --> 00:29:58.020
We'd been trying to talk to
this person for seven months.

00:29:58.020 --> 00:30:00.120
So trust-building takes time.

00:30:00.120 --> 00:30:01.860
It takes persistence.

00:30:01.860 --> 00:30:04.910
But he hadn't talked
about what happened

00:30:04.910 --> 00:30:07.790
to him there for 23 years.

00:30:07.790 --> 00:30:10.650
And he finally spoke to us.

00:30:10.650 --> 00:30:12.470
And to be trusted
with somebody's story

00:30:12.470 --> 00:30:17.960
like that-- it's an amazing
thing, and something

00:30:17.960 --> 00:30:20.630
that you carry with
you all the time.

00:30:20.630 --> 00:30:23.825
Your trust with these people
who give you their stories.

00:30:27.030 --> 00:30:29.010
I can still remember
conversations

00:30:29.010 --> 00:30:32.905
that I had where I remember
knocking on somebody's door

00:30:32.905 --> 00:30:36.130
and interviewing them
about something terrible

00:30:36.130 --> 00:30:37.700
their son had done.

00:30:37.700 --> 00:30:41.620
And I was talking to this
man, the guy's father,

00:30:41.620 --> 00:30:45.820
and this big, burly
Irishman burst into tears.

00:30:45.820 --> 00:30:48.210
And I was just like,
"Oh my goodness!"

00:30:48.210 --> 00:30:53.630
And that is the amazing part
of being a reporter, I think,

00:30:53.630 --> 00:30:56.240
is those kinds of
experiences that you

00:30:56.240 --> 00:30:57.900
have that stay with you.

00:30:57.900 --> 00:30:59.960
And become part of the
story that you then

00:30:59.960 --> 00:31:02.204
share with other people.

00:31:02.204 --> 00:31:03.870
ALISA BARBA: But
there's plenty of doors

00:31:03.870 --> 00:31:05.812
that get slammed
in your face too.

00:31:05.812 --> 00:31:08.270
You've got the guy bursting in
tears, and then you've got--

00:31:08.270 --> 00:31:10.310
I mean, I remember
as a reporter--

00:31:10.310 --> 00:31:13.440
I worked for the
MacNeil/Lehrer NewsHour,

00:31:13.440 --> 00:31:16.590
and I was on the Middle
East beat out of Washington.

00:31:16.590 --> 00:31:18.950
And part of my job
was-- I don't know,

00:31:18.950 --> 00:31:20.820
it's probably all before
everybody's time--

00:31:20.820 --> 00:31:25.130
but there was a bunch of
hostages being held in Iran.

00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:26.330
And across the Middle East.

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:28.080
I don't really remember
the circumstances.

00:31:28.080 --> 00:31:30.330
But my job, every time
there was news about this,

00:31:30.330 --> 00:31:33.440
was to call the families
and to get a quote.

00:31:33.440 --> 00:31:36.630
So there's nastiness too.

00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:38.080
Real nastiness.

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:40.121
ANDY DONOHUE: Just to
build on that a little bit.

00:31:40.121 --> 00:31:42.740
It's interesting how important,
in these kind of stories, just

00:31:42.740 --> 00:31:43.830
story selection is.

00:31:43.830 --> 00:31:45.600
Like, picking the right stories.

00:31:45.600 --> 00:31:49.500
Because you do spend a year,
18 months, on the story.

00:31:49.500 --> 00:31:51.496
And it is a high-wire act.

00:31:51.496 --> 00:31:53.370
It's amazing to me how
many different stories

00:31:53.370 --> 00:31:56.294
I've done that that key
source didn't come out

00:31:56.294 --> 00:31:57.210
till right at the end.

00:31:57.210 --> 00:31:58.990
And you're like,
"What the hell would

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:02.140
this nine months of my life
been if this person hadn't

00:32:02.140 --> 00:32:04.490
out of the blue emailed
me and decided to talk?"

00:32:04.490 --> 00:32:06.370
And so if you're
a daily reporter,

00:32:06.370 --> 00:32:10.120
you pick the wrong story,
that that scar lasts for a day

00:32:10.120 --> 00:32:11.740
and you move onto the next one.

00:32:11.740 --> 00:32:13.180
And so actually
like figuring out

00:32:13.180 --> 00:32:15.210
how to pick the right
stories, and when

00:32:15.210 --> 00:32:18.635
to give up on one when
it's not bearing fruit

00:32:18.635 --> 00:32:23.014
is really, really
tough calculus.

00:32:23.014 --> 00:32:24.930
RICHARD GINGRAS: We're
going to go to the Dory

00:32:24.930 --> 00:32:26.388
and then we'll come
back to Maggie.

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:34.710
"As nonprofit
organizations, how do you

00:32:34.710 --> 00:32:37.250
ensure that donors
and their donations

00:32:37.250 --> 00:32:42.309
never influence your reporting?"

00:32:42.309 --> 00:32:43.350
ROBIN FIELDS: It's funny.

00:32:43.350 --> 00:32:46.656
In my previous life, in
commercial journalism,

00:32:46.656 --> 00:32:48.905
we had the same question but
it was about advertisers.

00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:54.370
This is an issue
that we've always

00:32:54.370 --> 00:32:56.650
dealt with in journalism.

00:32:56.650 --> 00:32:59.280
And I think that independence
is just something

00:32:59.280 --> 00:33:01.350
that you accrue every day.

00:33:01.350 --> 00:33:03.130
I mean, I can sit here
and say, of course

00:33:03.130 --> 00:33:05.220
our donors have nothing to
do with the stories we choose

00:33:05.220 --> 00:33:05.969
or how we do them.

00:33:05.969 --> 00:33:07.610
And that's completely true.

00:33:07.610 --> 00:33:12.490
But you'll be the judge of
that by seeing what we do

00:33:12.490 --> 00:33:15.380
and how we do it.

00:33:15.380 --> 00:33:20.030
We are very, very
scrupulous about what

00:33:20.030 --> 00:33:22.690
strings we will allow to
be attached to any money

00:33:22.690 --> 00:33:23.640
that we take.

00:33:23.640 --> 00:33:29.200
We would never, for example,
take money to do a story.

00:33:29.200 --> 00:33:32.330
Because investigative reporting
goes where it goes, and we're

00:33:32.330 --> 00:33:37.220
not going to be limited in what
we report by virtue of promises

00:33:37.220 --> 00:33:39.620
that we make like that.

00:33:39.620 --> 00:33:43.420
And we've set up a lot of
limits on that kind of thing,

00:33:43.420 --> 00:33:45.580
to make sure that
that never happens.

00:33:45.580 --> 00:33:49.537
But again, independence is--
the proof is in the pudding.

00:33:49.537 --> 00:33:51.120
RICHARD GINGRAS: You
know, I've always

00:33:51.120 --> 00:33:53.560
felt that having worked
in public broadcasting

00:33:53.560 --> 00:33:56.610
myself, as well as in
commercial media, there

00:33:56.610 --> 00:33:58.200
is no revenue model.

00:33:58.200 --> 00:34:01.230
There is no financial
support model for journalism

00:34:01.230 --> 00:34:04.300
that doesn't come with the
potential for conflict.

00:34:04.300 --> 00:34:07.500
It is, as you say,
in the fastidiousness

00:34:07.500 --> 00:34:09.760
of those in that
organization do adhere

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:13.699
to the principles of how
and why you do what you do

00:34:13.699 --> 00:34:16.179
ANDY DONOHUE: I always say that
nonprofit journalism is not

00:34:16.179 --> 00:34:20.380
any more holy than for-profit.

00:34:20.380 --> 00:34:24.270
It is just as much dependent on
the firewalls and the systems

00:34:24.270 --> 00:34:26.909
you set up.

00:34:26.909 --> 00:34:29.280
There's these interesting
sort of sweet spots

00:34:29.280 --> 00:34:30.080
you have to find.

00:34:30.080 --> 00:34:33.070
Because when you do get
grants, people generally

00:34:33.070 --> 00:34:35.639
want to have an idea
of what kind of stuff

00:34:35.639 --> 00:34:36.790
you're going to cover.

00:34:36.790 --> 00:34:40.489
They may fund environmental
coverage, or something.

00:34:40.489 --> 00:34:43.920
So we have to figure out, yes,
we will undertake an endeavor

00:34:43.920 --> 00:34:46.800
to find out the most
toxic areas of California.

00:34:46.800 --> 00:34:49.020
But after that, you
don't get to pick.

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:50.092
That's a very broad area.

00:34:50.092 --> 00:34:51.050
We'll look at the data.

00:34:51.050 --> 00:34:53.425
But after that, you don't get
to pick what stories we do,

00:34:53.425 --> 00:34:54.800
who, does them.

00:34:54.800 --> 00:34:55.739
Anything like that.

00:34:55.739 --> 00:34:58.510
And so you can't get like really
on granular what stories you're

00:34:58.510 --> 00:35:00.010
doing, but at the
same time you have

00:35:00.010 --> 00:35:02.050
to figure out how you
can make what you're

00:35:02.050 --> 00:35:03.777
going to do appealing to donors.

00:35:03.777 --> 00:35:05.360
ALISA BARBA: And
just one last thought

00:35:05.360 --> 00:35:09.810
is I think donors or advertisers
or supporters or underwriters

00:35:09.810 --> 00:35:12.440
don't often understand that.

00:35:12.440 --> 00:35:14.720
What we take for
granted, and we know

00:35:14.720 --> 00:35:17.360
as the absolute basis of
funding for journalism.

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:22.360
There's a firewall between
editorial and fundraising.

00:35:22.360 --> 00:35:24.310
I would have to say
until very recently, I

00:35:24.310 --> 00:35:26.480
had absolutely nothing
to with fundraising.

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:28.780
But again, this is part
of the brave new world

00:35:28.780 --> 00:35:32.190
and we're all raising money
for our operations as we go.

00:35:32.190 --> 00:35:35.990
But oftentimes, funders
will be astonished

00:35:35.990 --> 00:35:39.184
to know that they can't have
a say in what the product is.

00:35:39.184 --> 00:35:40.600
ANDY DONOHUE: And
it's interesting

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:46.480
because I think people think
that because they're not

00:35:46.480 --> 00:35:49.290
a for-profit business,
that it may not be corrupt.

00:35:49.290 --> 00:35:49.790
Right?

00:35:49.790 --> 00:35:52.050
Or there may not be a
problem in asking for that.

00:35:52.050 --> 00:35:54.630
Because they're not
like an old card dealer

00:35:54.630 --> 00:35:57.452
at the newspaper hoping
to not get tough coverage.

00:35:57.452 --> 00:35:59.160
Like, they're not
making money off of it.

00:35:59.160 --> 00:36:00.366
They just have a viewpoint.

00:36:00.366 --> 00:36:02.990
But the fact of matter is, they
have a viewpoint and an agenda.

00:36:02.990 --> 00:36:05.000
And that can't drive
what we're doing, either.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:09.092
That's not as black and white
or as easy to explain to people.

00:36:09.092 --> 00:36:11.050
RICHARD GINGRAS: We're
going to Maggie Shields.

00:36:11.050 --> 00:36:13.160
Maggie Shields used
to work at the BBC.

00:36:13.160 --> 00:36:16.810
And then this weekend,
when I was hosting an AMA

00:36:16.810 --> 00:36:18.420
with Daniel Ellsberg,
the challenge

00:36:18.420 --> 00:36:20.885
was to as him a question that
he'd never been asked before.

00:36:20.885 --> 00:36:22.260
Which was a pretty
big challenge.

00:36:22.260 --> 00:36:23.840
And she won.

00:36:23.840 --> 00:36:25.465
So beware.

00:36:25.465 --> 00:36:27.405
AUDIENCE: My question
is about [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:03.030 --> 00:37:06.750
RICHARD GINGRAS: Basically, I'm
going to go at that last part.

00:37:06.750 --> 00:37:08.490
How do you, in
your work, do work

00:37:08.490 --> 00:37:12.510
that lasts longer than the
instance of the article?

00:37:12.510 --> 00:37:14.640
ANDY DONOHUE: That is
really important question

00:37:14.640 --> 00:37:18.570
that we're wrestling with right
now, because the old model

00:37:18.570 --> 00:37:22.590
that even CIR used to do, was
drop the big investigation

00:37:22.590 --> 00:37:24.200
and just walk away.

00:37:24.200 --> 00:37:26.790
And now online, you have
to have a community that's

00:37:26.790 --> 00:37:28.260
ready to take that.

00:37:28.260 --> 00:37:30.250
Unless it's just
some blockbuster.

00:37:30.250 --> 00:37:32.390
And so one thing that
we're working on right now

00:37:32.390 --> 00:37:37.640
is thinking of these as
investigations in context.

00:37:37.640 --> 00:37:42.810
So that we have, maybe,
researchers or newer reporters

00:37:42.810 --> 00:37:45.090
constantly writing about the
themes that we've decided

00:37:45.090 --> 00:37:46.880
are important.

00:37:46.880 --> 00:37:49.180
Public service kind of stuff,
or investigative things.

00:37:49.180 --> 00:37:51.470
So that there is sort of
an audience built up that's

00:37:51.470 --> 00:37:53.910
ready and knows we might be
interested in these things

00:37:53.910 --> 00:37:55.540
when the story drops.

00:37:55.540 --> 00:37:58.585
And then when the story drops--
this is an idea, actually,

00:37:58.585 --> 00:38:02.480
that the editor Stephen
Engelberg at ProPublica,

00:38:02.480 --> 00:38:03.970
I sort of stole from him.

00:38:03.970 --> 00:38:05.670
His idea that he
had talked about,

00:38:05.670 --> 00:38:07.640
and what they think
about is campaigns.

00:38:07.640 --> 00:38:09.990
Where you drop a
story, but then you

00:38:09.990 --> 00:38:11.710
have all these other
things that come out

00:38:11.710 --> 00:38:13.880
so that you find
ways to continuously

00:38:13.880 --> 00:38:18.660
be in the news cycle,
beyond just that one day.

00:38:18.660 --> 00:38:22.120
And then creating durable and
sustainable data, I think,

00:38:22.120 --> 00:38:24.210
is also a really important part.

00:38:24.210 --> 00:38:26.970
Because we put so much work
into the searchable data

00:38:26.970 --> 00:38:29.270
apps that we create,
that they can't just

00:38:29.270 --> 00:38:30.750
stand for that one story.

00:38:30.750 --> 00:38:32.960
They have to have uses beyond
what that one story is.

00:38:32.960 --> 00:38:37.320
RICHARD GINGRAS: In fact,
with ProPublica-- and this is

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:41.560
an example I often
cite-- you've continued

00:38:41.560 --> 00:38:44.920
to make available this
knowledge utility on the state

00:38:44.920 --> 00:38:47.080
of dialysis treatment centers.

00:38:47.080 --> 00:38:49.090
So I can understand
which one I should use,

00:38:49.090 --> 00:38:51.090
should I need that help.

00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:53.050
Does that play a part as well?

00:38:53.050 --> 00:38:56.005
ROBIN FIELDS: Well, that was
my project as a reporter,

00:38:56.005 --> 00:39:01.360
so now you're just--
[LAUGHING] Oh, yes!

00:39:01.360 --> 00:39:03.360
Absolutely.

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:09.510
We want to create resources
both for the consuming public

00:39:09.510 --> 00:39:13.270
and for the journalistic
community that have enduring

00:39:13.270 --> 00:39:19.510
value, and that can be refreshed
and renewed all the time.

00:39:19.510 --> 00:39:24.960
We want to-- first
of all, we follow up.

00:39:24.960 --> 00:39:28.240
We follow up relentlessly
on our investigations.

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:30.200
I think we've
probably done, I don't

00:39:30.200 --> 00:39:34.350
know, somewhere between 150
and 200 stories about fracking.

00:39:34.350 --> 00:39:38.830
And I can guarantee you right
now that if people are waiting

00:39:38.830 --> 00:39:41.504
for us to go away on that
one, we're not gonna.

00:39:41.504 --> 00:39:43.420
I don't want to reveal
the ending or anything,

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:46.160
but that's not going to happen.

00:39:46.160 --> 00:39:47.680
So that's part of it.

00:39:47.680 --> 00:39:53.980
And I think for something
like-- we created something

00:39:53.980 --> 00:39:58.050
for a project that we have yet
to do on patient harm, that

00:39:58.050 --> 00:40:01.510
is in itself-- we have a
Facebook community of thousands

00:40:01.510 --> 00:40:05.510
of members, and that in and of
itself has produced stories.

00:40:05.510 --> 00:40:08.390
And I'd anticipate that
that has a lifespan

00:40:08.390 --> 00:40:10.270
of many, many, many years.

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:14.370
So I think that, as Andy
was saying, that there's

00:40:14.370 --> 00:40:17.470
a lot of different ways that
we keep a project relevant.

00:40:17.470 --> 00:40:21.610
And we don't just drop
a bomb and run away.

00:40:21.610 --> 00:40:24.800
ALISA BARBA: You know,
we're six months old.

00:40:24.800 --> 00:40:30.470
[LAUGHTER]

00:40:30.470 --> 00:40:32.900
RICHARD GINGRAS: A question
from the cloud, as it were.

00:40:32.900 --> 00:40:35.760
"What role do amateur
bloggers and individuals

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:40.160
sharing ad hoc messages, photos,
and video via social media

00:40:40.160 --> 00:40:42.460
play in modern
investigative journalism?

00:40:42.460 --> 00:40:44.750
Does leveraging
these sources enable

00:40:44.750 --> 00:40:51.150
more targeted investments by
professional journalists?"

00:40:51.150 --> 00:40:55.180
ROBIN FIELDS: You know, I
think that from my perspective,

00:40:55.180 --> 00:41:01.510
that's been more of a resource
for breaking news in places

00:41:01.510 --> 00:41:03.990
that reporters
can't get to than it

00:41:03.990 --> 00:41:05.770
has been for
investigative reporters.

00:41:07.881 --> 00:41:09.630
RICHARD GINGRAS: Maybe
I'm incorrect here,

00:41:09.630 --> 00:41:11.730
but I thought
ProPublica specifically

00:41:11.730 --> 00:41:15.600
had, around one
area of exploration,

00:41:15.600 --> 00:41:17.220
sort of done crowdsourcing.

00:41:17.220 --> 00:41:19.120
ROBIN FIELDS: Oh, we
have done crowdsourcing.

00:41:19.120 --> 00:41:22.150
And we have done-- mostly
we do a very directed kind

00:41:22.150 --> 00:41:23.420
of crowdsourcing.

00:41:23.420 --> 00:41:25.640
We did a project
called Free the Files.

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:29.660
And that was about
political spending

00:41:29.660 --> 00:41:33.240
on political ads,
which at one time

00:41:33.240 --> 00:41:36.220
were very difficult to
track because the FCC,

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:39.110
at first, wasn't putting
any of this data online.

00:41:39.110 --> 00:41:41.030
They had to go to
television stations

00:41:41.030 --> 00:41:44.060
and say, give us
your political file.

00:41:44.060 --> 00:41:45.370
Who did that?

00:41:45.370 --> 00:41:46.700
Nobody.

00:41:46.700 --> 00:41:49.960
And then eventually they did
put some of this stuff online,

00:41:49.960 --> 00:41:54.780
and it was in completely
ridiculous, undigestible form,

00:41:54.780 --> 00:41:57.010
as these things are in
their first iteration.

00:41:57.010 --> 00:41:59.610
PDFs that nobody could
make hide nor hair of.

00:41:59.610 --> 00:42:03.780
And we harnessed a group
of more than 1,000 people

00:42:03.780 --> 00:42:08.960
to basically take that
mishmash and turn it into data.

00:42:08.960 --> 00:42:11.600
And we actually put
together a database

00:42:11.600 --> 00:42:15.570
of more than $1 billion of
TV spending in the run-up

00:42:15.570 --> 00:42:20.700
to the 2012
presidential election.

00:42:20.700 --> 00:42:22.680
And I think what that
showed was that if you

00:42:22.680 --> 00:42:28.910
can give the crowd an
interesting and vital task,

00:42:28.910 --> 00:42:32.770
and give them a way to do it in
a uniform and standardized way,

00:42:32.770 --> 00:42:37.850
that there is potential to
use that for investigations,

00:42:37.850 --> 00:42:40.250
and to use that just to
inform the public on something

00:42:40.250 --> 00:42:41.544
it needs to know.

00:42:41.544 --> 00:42:43.460
RICHARD GINGRAS: But to
the original point of,

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:46.480
can it stimulate
an investigation?

00:42:46.480 --> 00:42:48.480
What Daniel Ellsberg
would say if he was here,

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:53.400
and what he said loud and
clear on Saturday night, was

00:42:53.400 --> 00:42:55.930
how do we stimulate
more whistle-blowing?

00:42:55.930 --> 00:43:00.290
And how can journalists
find other additional ways

00:43:00.290 --> 00:43:02.730
to ferret out whistle-blowing?

00:43:02.730 --> 00:43:05.120
Because obviously the state
of affairs in whistle-blowing

00:43:05.120 --> 00:43:06.870
in the United States
isn't terribly good--

00:43:06.870 --> 00:43:07.994
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:43:07.994 --> 00:43:09.660
ROBIN FIELDS: Federal
government to stop

00:43:09.660 --> 00:43:10.827
prosecuting whistle-blowers?

00:43:10.827 --> 00:43:12.993
RICHARD GINGRAS: Which is,
of course, his key point,

00:43:12.993 --> 00:43:15.690
is we've had more whistle-blower
prosecutions in the last six

00:43:15.690 --> 00:43:18.406
years and we had
in the last 100.

00:43:18.406 --> 00:43:20.530
ALISA BARBA: Yeah, I think
whistle-blowers, though,

00:43:20.530 --> 00:43:22.275
are different than
amateur bloggers.

00:43:24.830 --> 00:43:27.170
That is much, much
more of a pointed--

00:43:27.170 --> 00:43:29.140
where they may go to
ProPublica, or they

00:43:29.140 --> 00:43:33.560
may go to CIR or
something like that.

00:43:33.560 --> 00:43:36.170
We use this thing called the
Public Inside Network, which

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:38.780
is a public media thing, where
we have people who basically

00:43:38.780 --> 00:43:40.970
signed up to kind of
provide us with stories.

00:43:40.970 --> 00:43:43.730
So this is, again,
targeted crowdsourcing

00:43:43.730 --> 00:43:46.780
of people who are already
kind of in your community.

00:43:46.780 --> 00:43:48.901
That's something we do a lot of.

00:43:48.901 --> 00:43:49.984
RICHARD GINGRAS: Question?

00:43:49.984 --> 00:43:51.470
Paul?

00:43:51.470 --> 00:43:52.970
AUDIENCE: So with
the rapid transfer

00:43:52.970 --> 00:43:58.140
from old ways of consuming
news to these new form

00:43:58.140 --> 00:44:03.680
factors and the context that
comes with their [INAUDIBLE],

00:44:03.680 --> 00:44:07.653
how is that changing the way in
which you package and deliver

00:44:07.653 --> 00:44:08.652
investigative reporting?

00:44:12.310 --> 00:44:16.160
ANDY DONOHUE: I think
in a very basic way

00:44:16.160 --> 00:44:19.050
you're thinking about
the mobile phone.

00:44:19.050 --> 00:44:21.217
I'm thinking about the phone
as I'm editing stories,

00:44:21.217 --> 00:44:22.466
and seeing what it looks like.

00:44:22.466 --> 00:44:23.100
Right?

00:44:23.100 --> 00:44:28.040
Now, a great narrative is a
great narrative no matter what.

00:44:28.040 --> 00:44:29.880
Long format isn't going away.

00:44:29.880 --> 00:44:33.960
But what we've tried
to do is give people

00:44:33.960 --> 00:44:36.350
a lot of different
entries into a story,

00:44:36.350 --> 00:44:38.100
and package it in
different ways depending

00:44:38.100 --> 00:44:41.330
on what kind of consumer
or what kind of condition

00:44:41.330 --> 00:44:43.630
you may be in when
you're consuming it.

00:44:43.630 --> 00:44:47.862
We just had a story last week
about the dangerous pesticides

00:44:47.862 --> 00:44:49.570
that are used in the
strawberry industry.

00:44:49.570 --> 00:44:52.370
That's an 8,000- word
narrative with five chapters,

00:44:52.370 --> 00:44:54.330
but it's also a
listicle, "Seven Things

00:44:54.330 --> 00:44:57.380
You Should Know Before You
Eat Your First Strawberry."

00:44:57.380 --> 00:45:00.380
It's also a quick,
four-minute animation

00:45:00.380 --> 00:45:03.170
that is narrated by Roman Mars.

00:45:03.170 --> 00:45:04.240
It's also data app.

00:45:04.240 --> 00:45:07.430
So it's just sort of finding
all these different ways.

00:45:07.430 --> 00:45:10.349
But then also making sure,
first and foremost when

00:45:10.349 --> 00:45:12.390
we're looking at what the
design is, that it just

00:45:12.390 --> 00:45:15.405
fits on the phone.

00:45:15.405 --> 00:45:16.280
RICHARD GINGRAS: Yes?

00:45:16.280 --> 00:45:19.352
AUDIENCE: I have a question
about data sources.

00:45:19.352 --> 00:45:23.772
[INAUDIBLE] Are there
any data sources

00:45:23.772 --> 00:45:26.604
that you wish you had access to?

00:45:26.604 --> 00:45:27.104
[INAUDIBLE]

00:45:30.020 --> 00:45:31.769
ROBIN FIELDS: I wish
I had subpoena power.

00:45:31.769 --> 00:45:36.359
[LAUGHTER]

00:45:36.359 --> 00:45:39.580
But I sense that's
not going to happen.

00:45:39.580 --> 00:45:46.130
But certainly, we use
any and all databases

00:45:46.130 --> 00:45:50.110
that we can get out of state,
local, and federal government.

00:45:50.110 --> 00:45:54.740
That's just sort of the standby.

00:45:54.740 --> 00:45:57.430
I think Dollars for Docs, which
has come up a couple times,

00:45:57.430 --> 00:46:02.540
and is our database that
we sort of scraped out

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:06.030
of, at that point, I
think, seven or eight--

00:46:06.030 --> 00:46:12.320
and now it's more than that--
drug companies' information

00:46:12.320 --> 00:46:15.307
that they've been forced to put
online because of settlements

00:46:15.307 --> 00:46:16.140
with the government.

00:46:16.140 --> 00:46:18.900
And they put it
online in the way

00:46:18.900 --> 00:46:20.400
exactly that you'd
think they would,

00:46:20.400 --> 00:46:23.480
so that no one could ever
possibly understand or use it.

00:46:23.480 --> 00:46:24.500
So we took all that.

00:46:24.500 --> 00:46:28.220
We scraped it together and made
a usable database out of it.

00:46:28.220 --> 00:46:30.340
And I think that that's
a lot of what we do,

00:46:30.340 --> 00:46:33.560
which is take data
which exists but make it

00:46:33.560 --> 00:46:37.700
into a useful and
accessible thing.

00:46:37.700 --> 00:46:40.840
A living thing.

00:46:40.840 --> 00:46:45.060
But we will accept interesting
and leaked data too,

00:46:45.060 --> 00:46:48.490
so if you happen
to know anybody--

00:46:48.490 --> 00:46:51.390
ANDY DONOHUE: Governments
could essentially half of us

00:46:51.390 --> 00:46:55.260
out of business if they
just made their data usable.

00:46:55.260 --> 00:46:57.366
Maybe I shouldn't say that.

00:46:57.366 --> 00:46:59.517
ALISA BARBA: I was
thinking the same thing.

00:46:59.517 --> 00:47:01.266
ROBIN FIELDS: I think
you're right, sadly.

00:47:01.266 --> 00:47:03.200
ALISA BARBA: We all of
us rely on government

00:47:03.200 --> 00:47:05.820
regulatory agencies,
basically, for our data.

00:47:05.820 --> 00:47:07.840
And most of it is
so unusable that we

00:47:07.840 --> 00:47:10.480
are employed to try to
figure out what it all means.

00:47:10.480 --> 00:47:12.511
And then to make
a story around it.

00:47:12.511 --> 00:47:14.760
But if, for instance, if
they had a whole bunch of you

00:47:14.760 --> 00:47:16.301
guys working for
them and they really

00:47:16.301 --> 00:47:18.360
could figure out how
to make data useful,

00:47:18.360 --> 00:47:19.682
then everybody would know.

00:47:19.682 --> 00:47:21.390
ANDY DONOHUE: I'd love
to be able to pose

00:47:21.390 --> 00:47:23.700
that question to our data team,
though, and get back to you.

00:47:23.700 --> 00:47:25.450
I know one thing that
we've struggled with

00:47:25.450 --> 00:47:28.770
is we do a decent amount
of work on farm workers.

00:47:28.770 --> 00:47:33.550
And there is almost
no reliable data

00:47:33.550 --> 00:47:36.460
because they're undocumented
workers who will just not

00:47:36.460 --> 00:47:38.520
interface with the
government in any way.

00:47:38.520 --> 00:47:41.300
So if you're dealing with
sexual abuse, sexual harassment,

00:47:41.300 --> 00:47:43.460
pesticide poisoning, all
these kind of things.

00:47:43.460 --> 00:47:46.072
There is some data on
it, but it's just junk.

00:47:46.072 --> 00:47:47.530
And so one of the
things that we've

00:47:47.530 --> 00:47:49.670
been trying to play
with is how to actually,

00:47:49.670 --> 00:47:53.010
are there interesting
ways to create that data.

00:47:53.010 --> 00:47:54.760
ROBIN FIELDS: Another
area which is always

00:47:54.760 --> 00:47:58.740
sort of a data disaster
that is really frustrating

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:01.420
is that anything having
to do with the courts

00:48:01.420 --> 00:48:05.290
is chopped up by jurisdiction.

00:48:05.290 --> 00:48:08.092
And everybody wants to know
national things about what's

00:48:08.092 --> 00:48:10.050
happening in criminal
justice, and there's just

00:48:10.050 --> 00:48:10.950
no way to do it.

00:48:13.610 --> 00:48:17.260
Forget about the civil system.

00:48:17.260 --> 00:48:19.890
I think that so much
is done state-to-state

00:48:19.890 --> 00:48:22.520
that we'd really benefit
from a national picture.

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:24.100
So that's something.

00:48:24.100 --> 00:48:25.600
I know last year
we did something

00:48:25.600 --> 00:48:28.790
on injuries involving
temp workers.

00:48:28.790 --> 00:48:31.970
And we ended up doing an
analysis that had never

00:48:31.970 --> 00:48:35.390
been undertaken before,
involving four or five states'

00:48:35.390 --> 00:48:37.840
worth of workers' comp data.

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:39.754
And it's just amazing that--

00:48:39.754 --> 00:48:40.920
ALISA BARBA: Nobody does it.

00:48:40.920 --> 00:48:42.461
ROBIN FIELDS: Yeah,
that isn't there.

00:48:42.461 --> 00:48:46.190
That we don't know the answers
to these very basic questions,

00:48:46.190 --> 00:48:47.739
even in the sea of
data that we have.

00:48:47.739 --> 00:48:48.530
ALISA BARBA: Right.

00:48:48.530 --> 00:48:49.570
It's sea of data.

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:52.990
So covering energy and
fracking, and you're

00:48:52.990 --> 00:48:56.440
trying to compare regulatory
climates in Pennsylvania, North

00:48:56.440 --> 00:48:58.940
Dakota, Texas, Colorado,
where it's all different

00:48:58.940 --> 00:49:03.380
and everybody posts it in a
different way, if they post it.

00:49:03.380 --> 00:49:03.880
Yeah.

00:49:03.880 --> 00:49:04.850
That's what we do.

00:49:04.850 --> 00:49:07.391
ANDY DONOHUE: Sorry to belabor
this, but one other thing too.

00:49:07.391 --> 00:49:10.590
I think in education there's
actually too much data.

00:49:10.590 --> 00:49:13.320
I feel like you can
find a piece of data

00:49:13.320 --> 00:49:15.300
to make every case you want.

00:49:15.300 --> 00:49:17.675
So it's like this
cacophony of data.

00:49:17.675 --> 00:49:20.786
ROBIN FIELDS: And the Department
of Education data is filthy.

00:49:20.786 --> 00:49:21.722
It's awful.

00:49:21.722 --> 00:49:23.910
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:49:23.910 --> 00:49:25.960
RICHARD GINGRAS:
It's all filthy.

00:49:25.960 --> 00:49:28.500
Probably our last
question, and I

00:49:28.500 --> 00:49:29.750
think it's an interesting one.

00:49:29.750 --> 00:49:33.560
It's how do you budget
a story, cost-wise?

00:49:33.560 --> 00:49:34.660
Which actually reminds me.

00:49:34.660 --> 00:49:37.730
I worked at CPB about
40 million years ago,

00:49:37.730 --> 00:49:40.730
and we were funding a
documentary series on death

00:49:40.730 --> 00:49:41.730
and dying.

00:49:41.730 --> 00:49:44.571
And the key
character was a woman

00:49:44.571 --> 00:49:46.320
who was suffering from
a terminal illness.

00:49:46.320 --> 00:49:48.672
And I was going to follow
her until her demise.

00:49:48.672 --> 00:49:51.130
And her prognosis at the time
we started it was six months.

00:49:51.130 --> 00:49:52.254
And then went to 12 months.

00:49:52.254 --> 00:49:54.020
And then it went to 18 months.

00:49:54.020 --> 00:49:58.790
Which, suffice to say, caused
a tremendous amount of angst

00:49:58.790 --> 00:50:00.690
on the part of the funders.

00:50:00.690 --> 00:50:03.312
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:03.312 --> 00:50:05.270
ROBIN FIELDS: You were
like, "There's good news

00:50:05.270 --> 00:50:06.830
and there's bad news."

00:50:06.830 --> 00:50:08.860
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:08.860 --> 00:50:12.130
RICHARD GINGRAS: So
how do you do it?

00:50:12.130 --> 00:50:16.060
ANDY DONOHUE: Well,
you really don't.

00:50:16.060 --> 00:50:19.770
I mean, I don't know that's
politically correct to say.

00:50:19.770 --> 00:50:22.190
But you kind of let the
stories go where they go.

00:50:22.190 --> 00:50:25.520
And if it's really good,
we find ways to pay for it.

00:50:25.520 --> 00:50:27.810
And if it's really
not good, then we

00:50:27.810 --> 00:50:30.990
try to shut down as
fast as possible.

00:50:30.990 --> 00:50:34.700
We had a donor event yesterday
based on the strawberry story,

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:37.260
and our executive
director estimated

00:50:37.260 --> 00:50:40.140
that it cost $500,000.

00:50:40.140 --> 00:50:42.600
And we had no way of
knowing that's what

00:50:42.600 --> 00:50:44.880
it was going to cost.

00:50:44.880 --> 00:50:48.164
I would hate to know if
I came in from the start

00:50:48.164 --> 00:50:50.330
and said, "Hey guys, this
is going to cost $500,000"

00:50:50.330 --> 00:50:52.114
if I would have
gotten it approved.

00:50:52.114 --> 00:50:53.530
But everybody kept
getting into it

00:50:53.530 --> 00:50:55.071
and it kept getting
more interesting.

00:50:55.071 --> 00:50:57.800
And so just kind of felt right.

00:50:57.800 --> 00:51:00.720
ROBIN FIELDS: Well, I think
also, just to keep in mind,

00:51:00.720 --> 00:51:03.735
the single-most expensive
item in any story

00:51:03.735 --> 00:51:06.510
is usually the
journalist's time.

00:51:06.510 --> 00:51:09.360
And it's as you were
saying, you don't

00:51:09.360 --> 00:51:11.250
know how long it will
take to do the story,

00:51:11.250 --> 00:51:15.170
but you're going to do
it till you've got it.

00:51:15.170 --> 00:51:19.030
And that's an unknowable
thing at the beginning,

00:51:19.030 --> 00:51:20.611
as you were saying.

00:51:20.611 --> 00:51:22.110
But that's the way
it's always been.

00:51:22.110 --> 00:51:24.520
It's interesting that
this issue of cost

00:51:24.520 --> 00:51:29.620
bubbles up to the surface
in organizations like ours.

00:51:29.620 --> 00:51:32.940
And yet it was exactly the
same at a traditional legacy

00:51:32.940 --> 00:51:36.190
organization, but it was sort
of hidden in a larger editorial

00:51:36.190 --> 00:51:39.470
budget, so you didn't
itemize these things.

00:51:39.470 --> 00:51:41.200
But I think in
smaller organizations

00:51:41.200 --> 00:51:45.620
that focus on very
resource-intensive work,

00:51:45.620 --> 00:51:49.600
that question is one that we
come up against all the time.

00:51:49.600 --> 00:51:51.520
RICHARD GINGRAS: So
we're almost out of time.

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:54.103
I'm going to close with a simple
question to all three of you.

00:51:54.103 --> 00:51:55.920
But before I do, I
want to A, thank you

00:51:55.920 --> 00:51:58.340
for your time and your
eloquence in being here today.

00:51:58.340 --> 00:51:59.840
And I also want to
say-- and I think

00:51:59.840 --> 00:52:02.090
I can speak for everyone
in the room-- I just

00:52:02.090 --> 00:52:05.040
want to thank you for the
tremendous work that you do.

00:52:05.040 --> 00:52:06.840
The passion you put into it.

00:52:06.840 --> 00:52:08.270
It's hugely important.

00:52:08.270 --> 00:52:12.130
And I know you do it
for higher purposes

00:52:12.130 --> 00:52:14.310
than making gobs
and gobs of money.

00:52:14.310 --> 00:52:19.250
In today's world that's
a remarkable thing.

00:52:19.250 --> 00:52:23.200
And I think we couldn't
thank you enough for that.

00:52:23.200 --> 00:52:25.400
But in closing, let's
add if each of you

00:52:25.400 --> 00:52:28.790
have a comment on,
again, what drives you?

00:52:28.790 --> 00:52:30.820
Why do you love what you do?

00:52:30.820 --> 00:52:34.150
What makes you get
up in the morning?

00:52:34.150 --> 00:52:36.410
ANDY DONOHUE: I think
this is the best

00:52:36.410 --> 00:52:39.550
time alive to be a
user of journalism.

00:52:39.550 --> 00:52:42.340
I mean, just the amount
of different sources.

00:52:42.340 --> 00:52:43.350
The way to get it.

00:52:43.350 --> 00:52:45.960
The democratization
of information.

00:52:45.960 --> 00:52:48.790
To me, it's just incredibly
exciting to be a part of that.

00:52:48.790 --> 00:52:50.550
I think we're at this
incredible moment

00:52:50.550 --> 00:52:55.980
where journalism completely
underwent a revolution

00:52:55.980 --> 00:52:57.480
over the last decade,
but we haven't

00:52:57.480 --> 00:53:00.220
known where that was
going to be going.

00:53:00.220 --> 00:53:02.080
And we're starting to
get a better sense.

00:53:02.080 --> 00:53:03.579
And I think-- as,
Richard, you write

00:53:03.579 --> 00:53:05.400
a lot-- this isn't a
thing where we're just

00:53:05.400 --> 00:53:07.170
going from A to B.
Now we're in a state

00:53:07.170 --> 00:53:08.790
of constant transformation.

00:53:08.790 --> 00:53:11.325
And that's really exciting, to
not just step in and do a job

00:53:11.325 --> 00:53:13.170
that people have always
done, but step in

00:53:13.170 --> 00:53:16.790
and do this job that gets
to be redefined every day.

00:53:16.790 --> 00:53:18.892
And to be a part of
that is just incredible.

00:53:18.892 --> 00:53:19.600
ALISA BARBA: Yes.

00:53:19.600 --> 00:53:20.100
Ditto.

00:53:20.100 --> 00:53:20.670
Absolutely.

00:53:20.670 --> 00:53:22.370
All that is awesome.

00:53:22.370 --> 00:53:25.670
I work with five or six
journalists who are all

00:53:25.670 --> 00:53:29.810
aged 28 to 32, and they are so
jazzed about what we're doing.

00:53:29.810 --> 00:53:30.860
They're so excited.

00:53:30.860 --> 00:53:33.170
They want to do
"Serial" podcasts.

00:53:33.170 --> 00:53:35.280
They want to do everything.

00:53:35.280 --> 00:53:38.040
For a legacy journalist,
it keeps me young.

00:53:38.040 --> 00:53:38.970
I love it.

00:53:38.970 --> 00:53:42.150
And just even from the get-go,
even back 30 years ago when

00:53:42.150 --> 00:53:45.630
I began, journalism
is the best job

00:53:45.630 --> 00:53:47.180
because you come in
to work every day

00:53:47.180 --> 00:53:50.350
and you learn something new
and you tell stories about it.

00:53:50.350 --> 00:53:52.659
So I just love it.

00:53:52.659 --> 00:53:54.110
RICHARD GINGRAS: Robin?

00:53:54.110 --> 00:53:57.520
ROBIN FIELDS: Well,
I think that what

00:53:57.520 --> 00:53:59.400
drives me is the
same thing that's

00:53:59.400 --> 00:54:02.226
driven ProPublica
from the start.

00:54:02.226 --> 00:54:04.600
We have this mission statement
that when we put out there

00:54:04.600 --> 00:54:07.730
I almost thought
it was too much.

00:54:07.730 --> 00:54:13.060
It talked about doing
stories of moral force.

00:54:13.060 --> 00:54:19.230
And I was almost embarrassed
to realize how much I actually

00:54:19.230 --> 00:54:22.370
believe in that.

00:54:22.370 --> 00:54:25.360
We're all supposed to be
hard-bitten, irreverent sorts,

00:54:25.360 --> 00:54:30.980
and not allow ourselves to
indulge in such thoughts.

00:54:30.980 --> 00:54:34.650
But actually, I really
do believe in that.

00:54:34.650 --> 00:54:38.060
And I do believe in
our job as reporters

00:54:38.060 --> 00:54:42.950
to bring accountability
and to bring transparency

00:54:42.950 --> 00:54:44.080
to this world.

00:54:44.080 --> 00:54:46.950
I believe that
without that, we can't

00:54:46.950 --> 00:54:49.250
have our country as it is.

00:54:49.250 --> 00:54:52.760
We need to have this
information to be citizens.

00:54:52.760 --> 00:54:56.020
And, I mean, as we've seen
over the last couple of years

00:54:56.020 --> 00:54:59.300
with the stories about the
NSA and so forth, there

00:54:59.300 --> 00:55:03.710
is such an important role for
journalists-- particularly

00:55:03.710 --> 00:55:09.970
investigative journalists-- to
play in keeping things the way

00:55:09.970 --> 00:55:11.990
we want them in this society.

00:55:11.990 --> 00:55:17.920
So anyway, still a
little embarrassed.

00:55:17.920 --> 00:55:20.364
But still a believer, I suppose.

00:55:20.364 --> 00:55:22.030
RICHARD GINGRAS:
You're talking to folks

00:55:22.030 --> 00:55:24.030
at a company that has the
motto "Don't do evil."

00:55:24.030 --> 00:55:26.460
So I think the moral
force thing actually

00:55:26.460 --> 00:55:28.260
registers quite
strongly with us.

00:55:28.260 --> 00:55:30.690
Thank you very, very much
for your being here today.

00:55:30.690 --> 00:55:34.940
[APPLAUSE]

